20/10/2010
ZAGREB, Croatia -- Former Deputy Prime Minister Damir Polancec was convicted on Tuesday (October 19th) of a second corruption charge after pleading guilty to abuse of power stemming from a business deal in his home town of Djelekovec.
He was given a suspended one-year sentence, with four years probation.
On Friday, he was sentenced to 15 months in prison, pending appeal, for spending budget funds on an unnecessary expert study.
Polancec is the highest ranking official sentenced for corruption in Croatia so far.
(HRT, Vecernji List, Radio Net, Reuters - 19/10/10)
